  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Pulpit Commentary",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_sub_title",
        "text": "Verse 28.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " - ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "They stripped him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐκδύσαντες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). Some manuscripts read ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "ἐνδύσαντες",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", \"when they had clothed him;\" but this seems to have been derived from St. Mark, and to be here somewhat tautological. They had heard of his claim to be a King, so they determined to deride him with the mockery of royal honours. They tore his garments from his mangled form, thus opening afresh his half-dried wounds. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "cmt_word",
        "text": "Put on him a scarlet robe",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greek",
        "text": "χλαμύδα κοκκίνην",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "). This was probably the short military woollen cloak worn by officers, in colour either scarlet or purple, and fastened by a buckle on the right shoulder. Some think it was a cast-off garment from the wardrobe of King Herod, which they found and appropriated to this purpose. Whatever it was, its bright hue was suitable for this mockery of regal splendour. Matthew 27:28",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
    ]
  },
